Direct `===` checks fail for many decimal calculations because JavaScript uses binary floating-point, so values like `0.1 + 0.2` become `0.30000000000000004` instead of exactly `0.3`.

Use an epsilon/tolerance comparison instead:

```js
const a = 0.1 + 0.2;
const b = 0.3;

if (Math.abs(a - b) < Number.EPSILON) {
  console.log('equal');
}
```

For a more practical reusable fix, use a slightly larger tolerance:

```js
function nearlyEqual(a, b, tolerance = 1e-10) {
  return Math.abs(a - b) <= tolerance;
}

if (nearlyEqual(0.1 + 0.2, 0.3)) {
  console.log('equal');
}
```

Use `Number.EPSILON` for tiny rounding differences near 1, and a custom tolerance for general-purpose comparisons.

