Debouncing collapses a burst of events into a single action. Each incoming event resets a timer, so the callback only runs after events have stopped for the configured delay. In event-driven systems, this is useful for noisy inputs like keystrokes, resize, or scroll events where reacting to every event would waste work.

```js
function debounce(callback, delay = 300) {
  let timeoutId;

  return function (...args) {
    const context = this;
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      callback.apply(context, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}
```

Usage:

```js
const debouncedLog = debounce((value) => {
  console.log(value);
}, 300);

debouncedLog('a');
debouncedLog('b');
debouncedLog('c');
// Only logs 'c' after 300 ms of no further calls.
```

