Pagination lets an API split a large result set into smaller responses so clients don’t request everything at once. A common pattern is token-based pagination: each response returns `items` plus a `nextPageToken`. You call the endpoint once, collect `items`, then keep calling it with that token until `nextPageToken` is missing or empty.

Typical flow:
1. Call endpoint with no token.
2. Read `response.items` and append them.
3. If `response.nextPageToken` exists, call again with that token.
4. Repeat until there is no next token.

This is usually better than offset-based pagination for changing datasets because tokens are often opaque cursors generated by the server.

```js
/**
 * Fetch all pages from a token-paginated endpoint.
 *
 * @param {(pageToken?: string) => Promise<{ items: any[], nextPageToken?: string }>} fetchPage
 * @returns {Promise<any[]>}
 */
async function fetchAllPages(fetchPage) {
  const allItems = [];
  let nextPageToken = undefined;

  do {
    const response = await fetchPage(nextPageToken);
    allItems.push(...response.items);
    nextPageToken = response.nextPageToken;
  } while (nextPageToken);

  return allItems;
}
```

Example usage:

```js
async function fetchUsersPage(pageToken) {
  const url = new URL('https://api.example.com/users');
  if (pageToken) url.searchParams.set('pageToken', pageToken);

  const res = await fetch(url);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return res.json();
}

const users = await fetchAllPages(fetchUsersPage);
console.log(users);
```

