**REST idempotency** means making the same request multiple times has the same intended effect on server state as making it once. `PUT` is idempotent because sending the same full representation to the same resource repeatedly should keep that resource in the same final state. The response may differ between calls (for example, timestamps or status codes), but the stored resource should converge to the same result.

Example:
- `PUT /users/123` with `{ "name": "Ada", "email": "ada@example.com" }`
- First call updates or creates user `123`
- Second identical call leaves user `123` in the same state

A simple Node/Express handler for **`PUT /users/:id`** that replaces the user record with the request body:

```js
import express from 'express';

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

// Example in-memory store
const users = new Map();

app.put('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  const replacement = req.body;

  // Replace the full record, forcing the path id to be authoritative
  const user = { ...replacement, id };

  const existed = users.has(id);
  users.set(id, user);

  res.status(existed ? 200 : 201).json(user);
});
```

If you want stricter full-replacement semantics, reject bodies that omit required fields:

```js
app.put('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  const { name, email } = req.body;

  if (typeof name !== 'string' || typeof email !== 'string') {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'name and email are required' });
  }

  const user = { id, name, email };
  const existed = users.has(id);
  users.set(id, user);

  res.status(existed ? 200 : 201).json(user);
});
```

