A greedy algorithm builds a solution step by step by always choosing the locally best option at the current moment. It works well when a problem has **greedy-choice property** (a locally optimal choice can lead to a globally optimal solution) and **optimal substructure** (after making a choice, the remaining problem is still an optimal subproblem).

For the **activity selection problem**, each activity has a start and end time, and we want the maximum number of non-overlapping activities. The greedy rule is:

- Sort activities by increasing **finish time**
- Always pick the next activity whose start time is at least the finish time of the last chosen one

Why this works:
- Picking the activity that finishes earliest leaves the most room for future activities
- Any optimal solution can be transformed to start with the earliest-finishing compatible activity without reducing the total number selected

## C++ solution

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace std;

struct Activity {
    int start;
    int end;
};

vector<Activity> selectActivities(vector<Activity> activities) {
    sort(activities.begin(), activities.end(), [](const Activity& a, const Activity& b) {
        if (a.end == b.end) return a.start < b.start;
        return a.end < b.end;
    });

    vector<Activity> selected;
    int lastEnd = -1;

    for (const auto& activity : activities) {
        if (selected.empty() || activity.start >= lastEnd) {
            selected.push_back(activity);
            lastEnd = activity.end;
        }
    }

    return selected;
}

int main() {
    vector<Activity> activities = {
        {1, 4}, {3, 5}, {0, 6}, {5, 7}, {3, 9},
        {5, 9}, {6, 10}, {8, 11}, {8, 12}, {2, 14}, {12, 16}
    };

    vector<Activity> result = selectActivities(activities);

    cout << "Selected activities:\n";
    for (const auto& activity : result) {
        cout << "[" << activity.start << ", " << activity.end << "]\n";
    }

    cout << "Maximum number of non-overlapping activities: " << result.size() << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

## Complexity
- Sorting: **O(n log n)**
- Selection scan: **O(n)**
- Total: **O(n log n)**

