A trie stores strings by shared prefixes. Each node represents a prefix, edges represent characters, and a word exists when you end on a node marked as terminal. This makes prefix operations efficient: inserting, exact lookup, and prefix checks all take **O(L)** time where **L** is the word length, regardless of how many words are stored.

For lowercase English words, a common implementation uses an array of 26 child pointers per node:
- `Insert(word)`: walk/create nodes for each character, then mark the last node as a word end.
- `Search(word)`: walk nodes; return `true` only if the final node is marked as a word end.
- `StartsWith(prefix)`: walk nodes; return `true` if the prefix path exists.

Here’s a simple C# implementation supporting `Insert`, `Search`, and `StartsWith`.

```csharp
using System;

public class Trie
{
    private class TrieNode
    {
        public TrieNode[] Children = new TrieNode[26];
        public bool IsWord;
    }

    private readonly TrieNode _root;

    public Trie()
    {
        _root = new TrieNode();
    }

    public void Insert(string word)
    {
        TrieNode current = _root;

        foreach (char c in word)
        {
            int index = c - 'a';
            if (current.Children[index] == null)
            {
                current.Children[index] = new TrieNode();
            }

            current = current.Children[index];
        }

        current.IsWord = true;
    }

    public bool Search(string word)
    {
        TrieNode node = Traverse(word);
        return node != null && node.IsWord;
    }

    public bool StartsWith(string prefix)
    {
        return Traverse(prefix) != null;
    }

    private TrieNode Traverse(string s)
    {
        TrieNode current = _root;

        foreach (char c in s)
        {
            int index = c - 'a';
            if (current.Children[index] == null)
            {
                return null;
            }

            current = current.Children[index];
        }

        return current;
    }
}
```

Example:

```csharp
var trie = new Trie();
trie.Insert("apple");

Console.WriteLine(trie.Search("apple"));     // true
Console.WriteLine(trie.Search("app"));       // false
Console.WriteLine(trie.StartsWith("app"));   // true

trie.Insert("app");
Console.WriteLine(trie.Search("app"));       // true
```

