A hash table stores key/value pairs by hashing each key into an array index, giving average-case **O(1)** insert, lookup, and delete.

### Core idea
- A **hash function** turns a key like `"apple"` into a number.
- That number is mapped into a bucket index with something like `hash % capacity`.
- Multiple keys can land in the same bucket; that’s called a **collision**.

### Separate chaining
With **separate chaining**, each bucket holds a small list of entries instead of a single value.
- On `set(key, value)`, hash the key, go to that bucket, and:
  - update the entry if the key already exists
  - otherwise append a new entry
- On `get(key)`, hash the key and scan that bucket’s list
- On `delete(key)`, hash the key and remove the matching entry from the bucket list

### Why it works well
If the hash function spreads keys evenly, each bucket stays short on average, so operations remain fast.

### Tradeoffs
- **Pros:** simple, handles collisions cleanly
- **Cons:** worst case can degrade to **O(n)** if many keys land in one bucket
- Real implementations usually **resize** when the load factor gets too high

Here’s a simple implementation in JavaScript for **string keys** and **integer values**:

```js
class HashMap {
  constructor(capacity = 16) {
    this.capacity = capacity;
    this.buckets = Array.from({ length: capacity }, () => []);
    this.size = 0;
  }

  _hash(key) {
    let hash = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < key.length; i++) {
      hash = (hash * 31 + key.charCodeAt(i)) >>> 0;
    }
    return hash % this.capacity;
  }

  set(key, value) {
    if (typeof key !== 'string') {
      throw new TypeError('Key must be a string');
    }
    if (!Number.isInteger(value)) {
      throw new TypeError('Value must be an integer');
    }

    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (const entry of bucket) {
      if (entry.key === key) {
        entry.value = value;
        return;
      }
    }

    bucket.push({ key, value });
    this.size++;
  }

  get(key) {
    if (typeof key !== 'string') {
      throw new TypeError('Key must be a string');
    }

    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (const entry of bucket) {
      if (entry.key === key) {
        return entry.value;
      }
    }

    return undefined;
  }

  has(key) {
    return this.get(key) !== undefined;
  }

  delete(key) {
    if (typeof key !== 'string') {
      throw new TypeError('Key must be a string');
    }

    const index = this._hash(key);
    const bucket = this.buckets[index];

    for (let i = 0; i < bucket.length; i++) {
      if (bucket[i].key === key) {
        bucket.splice(i, 1);
        this.size--;
        return true;
      }
    }

    return false;
  }
}

// Example usage
const map = new HashMap();
map.set('apple', 5);
map.set('banana', 7);
map.set('apple', 9);

console.log(map.get('apple'));  // 9
console.log(map.get('banana')); // 7
console.log(map.has('grape'));  // false
console.log(map.delete('banana')); // true
console.log(map.get('banana')); // undefined
console.log(map.size); // 1
```

