A monotonic queue is a deque kept in sorted order so the best element is always at the front. For sliding-window maximum, keep indices in **decreasing** order of their values:

- Before adding index `i`, pop from the back while `nums[back] <= nums[i]`.
- Push `i`.
- Remove the front if it is outside the current window.
- Once the first full window is formed, the front holds the maximum.

This makes every index enter and leave the deque at most once, so the algorithm is **O(n)** time and **O(k)** space.

```js
function maxSlidingWindow(nums, k) {
  if (k <= 0 || nums.length === 0) return [];

  const deque = []; // stores indices, values are decreasing
  const result = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    while (deque.length && deque[0] <= i - k) {
      deque.shift();
    }

    while (deque.length && nums[deque[deque.length - 1]] <= nums[i]) {
      deque.pop();
    }

    deque.push(i);

    if (i >= k - 1) {
      result.push(nums[deque[0]]);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

Example:

```js
console.log(maxSlidingWindow([1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7], 3));
// [3, 3, 5, 5, 6, 7]
```

If you want, I can also give the same solution as a LeetCode-style class-based `MonotonicQueue` implementation.

