786.answer:
A mutex lock protects shared data so only one thread at a time can enter the critical section that reads or modifies it.

### Mutex lock pattern
- **Shared resource**: data accessed by multiple threads, like a counter.
- **Critical section**: the code that touches that shared data.
- **Lock before access**: a thread acquires the mutex before entering the critical section.
- **Unlock after access**: once done, it releases the mutex so another thread can proceed.

Without a mutex, operations like `counter++` are not safely atomic across threads: multiple threads can read the same old value and overwrite each other.

### Preferred C++ pattern
Use RAII with `std::lock_guard<std::mutex>` so the mutex is always released automatically when the scope ends.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <mutex>
#include <thread>
#include <vector>

class ThreadSafeCounter {
public:
    void increment() {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mutex_);
        ++value_;
    }

    int get() const {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mutex_);
        return value_;
    }

private:
    mutable std::mutex mutex_;
    int value_ = 0;
};

int main() {
    ThreadSafeCounter counter;
    constexpr int numThreads = 8;
    constexpr int incrementsPerThread = 100000;

    std::vector<std::thread> workers;
    workers.reserve(numThreads);

    for (int i = 0; i < numThreads; ++i) {
        workers.emplace_back([&counter]() {
            for (int j = 0; j < incrementsPerThread; ++j) {
                counter.increment();
            }
        });
    }

    for (auto& worker : workers) {
        worker.join();
    }

    std::cout << "Final counter value: " << counter.get() << '\n';
    std::cout << "Expected value: " << numThreads * incrementsPerThread << '\n';

    return 0;
}
```

### Why this is thread-safe
- `increment()` locks the mutex before modifying `value_`.
- `get()` also locks the mutex before reading `value_`.
- Only one thread can hold the mutex at a time, so no two threads race on `value_`.

### Compile
```bash
g++ -std=c++17 -pthread counter.cpp -o counter
```

If you want, I can also show the same counter using `std::atomic<int>` and explain when that is better than a mutex.

