A semaphore controls how many threads can access a shared resource at the same time. It keeps a counter of available permits: acquiring decrements the counter, and releasing increments it. If no permits remain, additional threads wait until one is released.

For a resource pool with **3 concurrent permits**, at most 3 threads can use the pool simultaneously.

```java
import java.util.concurrent.Semaphore;

public class ResourcePool {
    private final Semaphore semaphore = new Semaphore(3);

    public void useResource(String threadName) {
        try {
            semaphore.acquire();
            System.out.println(threadName + " acquired a permit. Available: " + semaphore.availablePermits());

            // Simulate using the shared resource
            Thread.sleep(2000);

            System.out.println(threadName + " finished using the resource.");
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            System.out.println(threadName + " was interrupted.");
        } finally {
            semaphore.release();
            System.out.println(threadName + " released a permit. Available: " + semaphore.availablePermits());
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ResourcePool pool = new ResourcePool();

        for (int i = 1; i <= 6; i++) {
            String threadName = "Thread-" + i;
            new Thread(() -> pool.useResource(threadName)).start();
        }
    }
}
```

### How it works
- `new Semaphore(3)` creates 3 permits.
- `acquire()` blocks if all 3 are in use.
- `release()` returns a permit so another thread can proceed.
- With 6 threads, only 3 run inside the critical section at once.

