The Strategy pattern defines a family of algorithms, puts each one in its own class/object, and makes them interchangeable at runtime. It’s useful when you want to change behavior without filling your code with `if/else` or `switch` logic.

### Why use it
- Encapsulates each algorithm separately
- Lets you swap behavior at runtime
- Keeps the main context class simple
- Makes adding new strategies easier

### In this example
We’ll model a `PaymentProcessor` that delegates payment handling to interchangeable strategies:
- `CreditCardPayment`
- `PayPalPayment`
- `BankTransferPayment`

### JavaScript implementation
```js
class PaymentProcessor {
  constructor(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  setStrategy(strategy) {
    this.strategy = strategy;
  }

  pay(amount) {
    if (!this.strategy || typeof this.strategy.pay !== 'function') {
      throw new Error('A valid payment strategy is required.');
    }

    return this.strategy.pay(amount);
  }
}

class CreditCardPayment {
  constructor(cardNumber, cardHolder) {
    this.cardNumber = cardNumber;
    this.cardHolder = cardHolder;
  }

  pay(amount) {
    return `Paid $${amount} with credit card ending in ${this.cardNumber.slice(-4)} for ${this.cardHolder}.`;
  }
}

class PayPalPayment {
  constructor(email) {
    this.email = email;
  }

  pay(amount) {
    return `Paid $${amount} using PayPal account ${this.email}.`;
  }
}

class BankTransferPayment {
  constructor(accountNumber, bankName) {
    this.accountNumber = accountNumber;
    this.bankName = bankName;
  }

  pay(amount) {
    return `Paid $${amount} via bank transfer from account ending in ${this.accountNumber.slice(-4)} at ${this.bankName}.`;
  }
}

// Usage
const processor = new PaymentProcessor(
  new CreditCardPayment('4111111111111111', 'Alice Doe')
);
console.log(processor.pay(100));

processor.setStrategy(new PayPalPayment('alice@example.com'));
console.log(processor.pay(75));

processor.setStrategy(new BankTransferPayment('9876543210', 'Example Bank'));
console.log(processor.pay(250));
```

### Example output
```txt
Paid $100 with credit card ending in 1111 for Alice Doe.
Paid $75 using PayPal account alice@example.com.
Paid $250 via bank transfer from account ending in 3210 at Example Bank.
```

### Key idea
`PaymentProcessor` doesn’t need to know *how* each payment works. It only depends on a common interface: each strategy must provide a `pay(amount)` method.

