794.answer:
The Command pattern encapsulates an action as an object, so the caller can trigger behavior without knowing the receiver details. It’s useful for decoupling senders from receivers, supporting queues/logging, and enabling undo by pairing each command with an inverse operation.

```js
class Light {
  constructor() {
    this.isOn = false;
  }

  on() {
    this.isOn = true;
    console.log('Light is ON');
  }

  off() {
    this.isOn = false;
    console.log('Light is OFF');
  }
}

class Command {
  execute() {
    throw new Error('execute() must be implemented');
  }

  undo() {
    throw new Error('undo() must be implemented');
  }
}

class LightOnCommand extends Command {
  constructor(light) {
    super();
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.on();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.off();
  }
}

class LightOffCommand extends Command {
  constructor(light) {
    super();
    this.light = light;
  }

  execute() {
    this.light.off();
  }

  undo() {
    this.light.on();
  }
}

class RemoteControl {
  constructor() {
    this.history = [];
  }

  submit(command) {
    command.execute();
    this.history.push(command);
  }

  undoLast() {
    const command = this.history.pop();
    if (!command) {
      console.log('Nothing to undo');
      return;
    }
    command.undo();
  }
}

// Usage
const light = new Light();
const lightOn = new LightOnCommand(light);
const lightOff = new LightOffCommand(light);
const remote = new RemoteControl();

remote.submit(lightOn);  // Light is ON
remote.submit(lightOff); // Light is OFF
remote.undoLast();       // Light is ON
remote.undoLast();       // Light is OFF
remote.undoLast();       // Nothing to undo
```

Structure:
- **Receiver**: `Light`
- **Command interface/base**: `Command`
- **Concrete commands**: `LightOnCommand`, `LightOffCommand`
- **Invoker**: `RemoteControl`

If you want, I can also show a version using plain objects instead of classes.

