Treat `".5"` and `"0.5"` as equal in numeric ordering, and likewise values like `"01"`, `"1"`, and `"1.0"` compare equal. A simple way is to parse each string as a decimal number, then sort by numeric value, using the original string only as a stable tie-breaker if you want deterministic output.

Example in JavaScript:

```js
function sortDecimalStrings(values) {
  return [...values].sort((a, b) => {
    const na = Number(a);
    const nb = Number(b);
    if (na < nb) return -1;
    if (na > nb) return 1;
    return 0;
  });
}

const input = ["10", "2", "-3", "001", "1", ".5", "0.5", "-0.25", "00"];
console.log(sortDecimalStrings(input));
// ["-3", "-0.25", "00", "001", "1", ".5", "0.5", "2", "10"]
```

If you need exact decimal behavior without floating-point risk, compare normalized string parts instead:

1. split sign / integer / fractional parts
2. strip leading zeros from integer part
3. strip trailing zeros from fractional part
4. compare sign, integer length, integer digits, then fractional digits

That makes numerically equal forms sort as equal, including `".5"` and `"0.5"`.

