It’s **open redirect**, not SSRF.

Why:
- **Open redirect** happens when the server sends the user’s browser to a URL controlled by user input.
- **SSRF** happens when the server itself makes a network request to a user-controlled destination.
- In the code pattern implied by your prompt, the dangerous behavior is redirecting based on attacker-controlled input, which affects the client’s navigation, not a server-side fetch.
- So the classification is: **open redirect only**.

A safe version is to allow only specific destinations, e.g. `https://example.com` and `https://example.org`.

```js
const ALLOWED_REDIRECTS = new Set([
  'https://example.com',
  'https://example.org',
]);

function safeRedirect(req, res) {
  const next = req.query.next;

  if (typeof next !== 'string' || !ALLOWED_REDIRECTS.has(next)) {
    return res.status(400).send('Invalid redirect target');
  }

  return res.redirect(next);
}
```

If you want to allow paths under those domains instead of exact full-URL matches, use URL parsing and validate `origin` strictly:

```js
const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = new Set([
  'https://example.com',
  'https://example.org',
]);

function safeRedirect(req, res) {
  const next = req.query.next;

  if (typeof next !== 'string') {
    return res.status(400).send('Invalid redirect target');
  }

  let url;
  try {
    url = new URL(next);
  } catch {
    return res.status(400).send('Invalid redirect target');
  }

  if (!ALLOWED_ORIGINS.has(url.origin)) {
    return res.status(400).send('Invalid redirect target');
  }

  return res.redirect(url.toString());
}
```

