```go
package service

import (
	"encoding/json"
	"errors"
)

type Payload struct {
	User   User              `json:"user"`
	Items  []Item            `json:"items"`
	Meta   map[string]string `json:"meta"`
	Action string            `json:"action"`
}

type User struct {
	ID   string `json:"id"`
	Name string `json:"name"`
}

type Item struct {
	SKU string `json:"sku"`
	Qty int    `json:"qty"`
}

func HandleRequest(body []byte) error {
	payload, err := parsePayload(body)
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}

	if err := validatePayload(payload); err != nil {
		return err
	}
	if err := processItems(payload); err != nil {
		return err
	}
	if err := auditRequest(payload); err != nil {
		return err
	}

	return nil
}

func parsePayload(body []byte) (*Payload, error) {
	var payload Payload
	if err := json.Unmarshal(body, &payload); err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	return &payload, nil
}

func validatePayload(p *Payload) error {
	if p.User.ID == "" {
		return errors.New("missing user id")
	}
	if len(p.Items) == 0 {
		return errors.New("missing items")
	}
	return nil
}

func processItems(p *Payload) error {
	for _, item := range p.Items {
		_ = item
	}
	return nil
}

func auditRequest(p *Payload) error {
	_ = p.Meta
	_ = p.Action
	return nil
}
```

**Bottleneck**
- Repeated `json.Unmarshal(body, &x)` in multiple helpers is the bottleneck.
- JSON unmarshalling is relatively expensive because each call reparses the full payload and reallocates decoded structures.

**Before**
Typical anti-pattern:
```go
func validate(body []byte) error {
	var p Payload
	return json.Unmarshal(body, &p)
}

func process(body []byte) error {
	var p Payload
	return json.Unmarshal(body, &p)
}

func audit(body []byte) error {
	var p Payload
	return json.Unmarshal(body, &p)
}
```

If payload size is `n` and there are `k` helpers doing this per request:
- Time: **O(k·n)**
- Extra decode space across the request flow: **O(n)** per unmarshal call, repeated `k` times in practice

**After**
- Unmarshal once at the request boundary.
- Pass `*Payload` to downstream helpers.

If helpers only read the parsed struct:
- Time: **O(n + k)**, commonly simplified to **O(n)** when helper logic is constant or proportional only to accessed fields
- Space: **O(n)** for one parsed representation

**Why this is better**
- Removes repeated full-payload parsing
- Reduces allocations and GC pressure
- Centralizes validation/parsing at the boundary
- Makes helpers deterministic and easier to test since they operate on typed data instead of raw JSON

If you want, I can also show this as a minimal diff from a “before” code sample with benchmarks using `testing.B`.

