Use a cached per-type property map so reflection runs once per CLR type instead of once per object instance.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Reflection;

public static class Serializer
{
    private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, PropertyInfo[]> PropertyCache = new();

    public static Dictionary<string, object?> SerializeObject(object obj)
    {
        var type = obj.GetType();
        var properties = PropertyCache.GetOrAdd(type, static t =>
            t.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public)
             .Where(p => p.CanRead)
             .ToArray());

        var result = new Dictionary<string, object?>(properties.Length);
        foreach (var property in properties)
        {
            result[property.Name] = property.GetValue(obj);
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

If you also want to reduce `GetValue` overhead, cache compiled getters too:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Linq.Expressions;
using System.Reflection;

public static class Serializer
{
    private sealed record PropertyAccessor(string Name, Func<object, object?> Get);

    private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, PropertyAccessor[]> AccessorCache = new();

    public static Dictionary<string, object?> SerializeObject(object obj)
    {
        var accessors = AccessorCache.GetOrAdd(obj.GetType(), BuildAccessors);
        var result = new Dictionary<string, object?>(accessors.Length);

        foreach (var accessor in accessors)
        {
            result[accessor.Name] = accessor.Get(obj);
        }

        return result;
    }

    private static PropertyAccessor[] BuildAccessors(Type type)
    {
        return type
            .GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public)
            .Where(p => p.CanRead)
            .Select(p => new PropertyAccessor(p.Name, BuildGetter(type, p)))
            .ToArray();
    }

    private static Func<object, object?> BuildGetter(Type declaringType, PropertyInfo property)
    {
        var objParam = Expression.Parameter(typeof(object), "obj");
        var typedObj = Expression.Convert(objParam, declaringType);
        var propertyAccess = Expression.Property(typedObj, property);
        var boxedResult = Expression.Convert(propertyAccess, typeof(object));
        return Expression.Lambda<Func<object, object?>>(boxedResult, objParam).Compile();
    }
}
```

### Bottleneck
The expensive part is calling reflection-based metadata discovery like `GetProperties()` inside the hot loop for every instance. Reflection walks type metadata, allocates arrays, and may perform filtering every time. In a serializer processing many objects of the same type, that repeated metadata lookup is wasted work.

### Big-O
Let:
- `n` = number of objects serialized
- `p` = number of public readable properties on the type

#### Before caching
Per object:
- discover properties: `O(p)`
- read property values: `O(p)`

Total: **`O(n * p + n * p)` = `O(n * p)`**

Even though the asymptotic form stays `O(n * p)`, the constant factor is much worse because reflection discovery happens `n` times.

#### After caching property metadata
One-time per type:
- discover properties: `O(p)`

Per object:
- read property values: `O(p)`

Total: **`O(p) + O(n * p)` = `O(n * p)`**

Same asymptotic complexity for one type, but much lower real cost because metadata discovery drops from `n` times to `1` time per type.

#### After caching compiled getters
One-time per type:
- discover properties + build getters: `O(p)`

Per object:
- invoke cached getters: `O(p)`

Total remains **`O(n * p)`**, but with another constant-factor improvement by avoiding slower reflective `PropertyInfo.GetValue()` calls.

### Practical summary
- **Main fix:** cache `PropertyInfo[]` by `Type`
- **Further optimization:** cache compiled delegates for property access
- **Result:** same Big-O, substantially better throughput and fewer allocations in tight loops

955.answer:
The bottleneck is the repeated **linear scan** through the 1M-ID vector for every query.

### Before
Typical pattern:
```cpp
bool contains(const std::vector<int>& ids, int q) {
    for (int id : ids) {
        if (id == q) return true;
    }
    return false;
}
```

If you do this for **10M queries** against **1M IDs**:
- **Per lookup:** `O(N)`
- **Total:** `O(Q * N)`
- With `Q = 10,000,000`, `N = 1,000,000` → about **10^13 comparisons** worst-case

That is the bottleneck.

### After
Precompute a hash set once, then do constant-time membership checks:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unordered_set>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> ids = /* 1M IDs */;
    std::vector<int> queries = /* 10M queries */;

    std::unordered_set<int> id_set;
    id_set.reserve(ids.size());
    id_set.insert(ids.begin(), ids.end());

    for (int q : queries) {
        if (id_set.contains(q)) {
            // found
        } else {
            // not found
        }
    }
}
```

If you're on pre-C++20, replace:
```cpp
id_set.contains(q)
```
with:
```cpp
id_set.find(q) != id_set.end()
```

### Big-O after optimization
- Build hash set: **`O(N)`**
- Per lookup: **average `O(1)`**
- Total queries: **average `O(Q)`**
- Overall: **`O(N + Q)`**

For `1M + 10M`, this is dramatically better than `O(Q * N)`.

### Why this helps
You trade a one-time preprocessing cost and extra memory for much faster lookups. For 10M membership checks, this is the right optimization.

### Alternative
If memory is tight and IDs can be sorted:
- Sort once: `O(N log N)`
- Query with `std::binary_search`: `O(log N)` per lookup
- Total: `O(N log N + Q log N)`

Example:
```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <vector>

std::sort(ids.begin(), ids.end());

for (int q : queries) {
    if (std::binary_search(ids.begin(), ids.end(), q)) {
        // found
    }
}
```

### Recommendation
- Use **`std::unordered_set`** for fastest average membership checks.
- Use **sorted vector + `std::binary_search`** if you want lower memory overhead and predictable performance.

